Text.Value: I'm not surprised. Gomwick always indulged him. And he's got a spark in his eye I don't like - looks lively.
Sit! Stay! Heel!
Is there any reward for returning him?
You - you got rid of her.
I'd kill her and take her place.
You were being awfully harsh on the boy when I arrived.
I'm sorry Scratch, there's nothing I can do.
I suspect she mistreats the dog and you, boy. Is this true?
Oh, yes please. I'd love to see him.
You again?
I can do whatever I please - he's my dog. Now get out - this is a private yard.
And now you have him. So get out of my kennels.

Get out. I'm short-handed, in case you've forgotten.

Nothing a smack or three of the rod won't fix.
Yeah. I'm caring for the courier dogs. Mar'hyah's my boss.
I'm sorry, Dringo - I only care about Scratch.
Oh gods.
I hope that bloody dog bites you.
He's a good dog. We'd both love to see him again.
Which means you're not a dog. So what the hell are you doing in my kennels?
Scratch! It's good to see you boy.
Fine. You think you can do a better job without me - be my guest.
Shut up, Dringo. And get back to work!
She seems like a bully.

Text.Value: I'll give you to the count of ten to leave these kennels. One, two...
You have lost your way, hound-keeper. Leave, before I teach you to respect these creatures properly.
A charming effort - but you can't fool me.
Bloody hell. Just leave.
I think I found one of your dogs - Scratch.
She's mean. But dad says she'll toughen me up.
This is a private kennels. Get out.
Your dad sounds like a smart man.
I think I found one of your dogs - Scratch.
He's forgotten his training. He'll be a terrible influence on the rest of your hounds.
It's not just Scratch. She's always hurting the dogs.

EditorData.NodeContext: Desperate, finally found someone to listen

Text.Value: It's the only way to teach him. He behaves worse than the dogs, and makes more of a mess.
What do you want?
I don't want to be alone again.

Text.Value: Gomwick was his handler, not his owner.
Dringo! Get back to work!
This dog is property of Sword Coast Couriers. I'll take him off your hands now.
True, boy, but only if you hone the anger she causes you. Make it sharp.
How I run my kennels is none of your concern. Take your mutt, and get out of my yard.

Text.Value: You might be able to bully a dog and a boy, but threaten me and I'll snap you in two.
They're a useless bunch of mongrels. You're welcome to them!
As for you - that's a tenday's pay docked. Now, back to work.
And you - what do you want? This is a private yard.
Recognise this dog? I think he belongs here.
I'll break every bone in your body before I let you hurt that dog.
You shouldn't raise your hand to him like that.
Found him, did you? I can't say I'm surprised - Gomwick never kept him on a tight leash.
Scratch! I thought he was dead.
This noble beast has tasted true freedom - he will never be brought to heel again.
Ah. You speak.
Give a rancid, rabid growl.
The harder you beat a dog, the more it bites back.
You're lucky I don't report you for stealing him in the first place.
I'm sorry for what happened. Scratch will be happier with you.
Hello.
Leave.
She's an educator. She says if somebody doesn't listen, shout louder. And if they still don't listen, fetch the rod.
That woman seems like a harsh taskmaster.
You're leaving me, Master?
You're leaving me, Mistress?

Text.Value: I should get back to work.
I beg your pardon?
Do you work here?
You don't look very tough.
I thought Scratch belonged to Gomwick?
They're worth more than their weight in gold.
I'll do a better job looking after these dogs than she ever did. I promise.
They're not for sale. These are courier dogs - trained to follow orders, read maps, and protect their deliveries with their lives.
Hello.
Bring him here and I'll give him a once-over for you. Check him for worms and so on.
Woof.
I thought we were pack.

You're leaving me?

Text.Value: Uhh, hi.
He is not 'property,' he is Scratch. Don't you dare threaten him.
It's fine. I have a very robust sense of humour.
I'd like to buy a dog.
He lives with me - you can't just take him.
Is this dog one of yours?
As for you, Dringo. Get out of my yard. You're finished here.
And if you do, I'll call the guards. Who do you think they'll side with? The dog is my property.
Sure she's not a bully? Abuse and strict training are far from the same, boy.
You - you'll do no such thing.

Text.Value: But - you should keep him...

Synopsis:
The player can talk to Marhyah or Dringo to mention they found Scratch. 
Depending on who the player spoke to first, either Dringo or Mat'hyah will be the initial speaker.
In either case, Mar'hyah will dominate the conversation.
Mar'hyah wants to reclaim him as property of the couriers' office. The player can convince her to release Scratch, and potentially even to leave the kennels altogether. If they fail to persuade her, Scracth is locked up, and Oyster Boy can get fired.
